Of the Symptoms

The symptoms supervening in this disease have to be considered. of these, the most common is diarrhoea, for the cure ol which mild cathartics‚ such as infusion of rhubarb, tamarinds, and sandal- wood, or a bolus compound of these, are specially uselul. Sometimes recourse must be had to astrin- gents and bland opiates, of which formulae are to be found here and there in books, but these are to be pre· ceded by purgation and sometimes also by a vomit.

In addition, immoderate sweating is apt to occur in this disorder. If this comes on in a lebrile paroxysm it may be critical, but it must not be rashly sup· pressed. But il it be inordinate and exceeding what might be expected from the cause, it is an indication that the body is loaded with cacochymical humours, and accordingly sweating of that sort is to be corrected by mild purgation repeated at intervals3 the purgation is to be brought about chiefly by rhubarb3 sometimes a vomit may be joined with it, nor should aperients and digestives be omitted.
